<item>
            <title>[DATACMNS-690] Multi-store silently ignores repository creation failures</title>
                <link>https://jira.spring.io/browse/DATACMNS-690</link>
                <project id="10510" key="DATACMNS">Spring Data Commons</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;Basic use case is presented here&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-data-examples/tree/master/multi-store&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-data-examples/tree/master/multi-store&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In my use case we did not put @Document on mongo annotations. Therefore, when I migrated our application to the latest version of spring boot (hence the latest version of spring data), my repositories were not created in the context.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It was very hard to guess that this happened as this is notified on a DEBUG level.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Fyi, we have a @Enable*Repositories which points to separate packages to avoid confusion on repository creation, therefore, it is was not trivial to understand the existence of this &quot;strict&quot; mode.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
